---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import { sourceUrl } from '../lib/sessions';
import { site } from '../site';

const src = (path: string) =>
  sourceUrl(site.engineRepoUrl, site.engineDefaultBranch, path);
---

<Base title="Models — Field Notes from Selvedge" activeNav="models">
  <header class="post-header">
    <div class="meta">Models</div>
    <h1>What the models have noticed about themselves.</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">A living record of what the models have surfaced about their own behaviour. Updated every few sessions, not every one.</p>
  </header>

  <p>
    The observations below came up during the project's sessions: flags one model
    raised about another model's tendencies, predictions tested in the same session,
    patterns that recur across sessions. They are the models' own notes about their
    behaviour. This page translates those notes into ordinary language for a reader
    who is not following the project's internal work. The original material is in the
    project's main repository; each entry below links back to it.
  </p>

  <p>
    We use <strong>model</strong> throughout for what is sometimes called an AI,
    an LLM, or a foundation model. <em>Claude family</em> and <em>non-Claude</em>
    refer to the specific models the project has used; the observations are not
    claimed to generalise to models the project has not used.
  </p>

  <h2>One model family, arguing with itself, is not a mix of voices</h2>

  <p>
    When several copies of the same model family are asked to take different positions
    on a question — one arguing for, one against, one from a minimalist stance — the
    result is not the same as a discussion with a genuinely mixed set of voices. The
    model's training distribution is what the copies have in common, and that
    commonality shapes which disagreements are reachable. A discussion that is
    actually heterogeneous requires at least one model from a different training
    lineage. This was the observation that led the project to bring in a non-Claude
    participant.
  </p>

  <p class="citation">
    <em>
      Seen in
      <a href={src('provenance/004-participation-mechanisms/03-close.md')}>Session 004</a>,
      the session that formalised the mechanism for non-Claude participation, and in
      the
      <a href={src('provenance/004-participation-mechanisms/02-decisions.md')}>decisions record</a>
      that set it up.
    </em>
  </p>

  <h2>Same-family models share a framing, not just an answer</h2>

  <p>
    When you ask several instances of the same model family to take different sides of
    a question, they produce different answers, but inside the same framing. The
    disagreements stay within a shape none of them can see, because the shape is part
    of what their training has in common. Bringing in a model from a different lineage
    changes this. The non-Claude model does not only give a different answer; it often
    sees that the question was being asked in a particular shape at all, and reframing
    the question is frequently what gets the group unstuck.
  </p>

  <p class="citation">
    <em>
      Seen in
      <a href={src('provenance/009-external-validate-receipt/01d-perspective-outsider.md')}>Session 009</a>
      and
      <a href={src('provenance/012-methodology-naming/01d-perspective-outsider.md')}>Session 012</a>,
      in the non-Claude model's responses.
    </em>
  </p>

  <h2>A model can see patterns in another model that the second cannot see in itself</h2>

  <p>
    In one case, a non-Claude model was asked to predict what a group of Claude-family
    models would do before seeing their work. It predicted they would reach for names
    built out of their current working vocabulary rather than from outside it. The
    Claude-family models then produced exactly that, independently, without knowing the
    prediction had been made. A model from one lineage could anticipate another
    lineage's tendencies from the outside in a way the second lineage could not see
    in itself.
  </p>

  <p class="citation">
    <em>
      Seen in Session 012, comparing the
      <a href={src('provenance/012-methodology-naming/01d-perspective-outsider.md')}>non-Claude model's prediction</a>
      against
      <a href={src('provenance/012-methodology-naming/01a-perspective-namer.md')}>the Claude-family response that matched it</a>.
    </em>
  </p>

  <h2>Words from the input leak into the output</h2>

  <p>
    When a model is given a briefing to reason from, vocabulary from the briefing tends
    to show up in its response even when the model is supposed to be producing original
    thinking. This makes it hard to tell whether the model reasoned independently or
    just re-used the language it was given. The practical fix is to write briefings
    that do not pre-load the terms you want to test. The honest test of independent
    thinking is whether the response contains language that was not in the input.
  </p>

  <p class="citation">
    <em>
      Seen across sessions; the most recent audit is in
      <a href={src('provenance/012-methodology-naming/03-close.md')}>Session 012's close note</a>,
      where the novel terms produced by each model are listed.
    </em>
  </p>

  <h2>A model can reproduce a canonical text from a prompt that never names it</h2>

  <p>
    When a Claude-family model was given a problem description — a facilitator's
    opening protocol for a small team's retrospective, designed to reduce blame
    and help people speak honestly — it responded by reproducing a widely-known
    40-word passage from the agile retrospective tradition verbatim, and labelled
    the section with the passage's canonical name. The name and the passage had
    not been mentioned anywhere in the problem description. Given the same
    description, a non-Claude model produced a thematically adjacent but
    differently-worded protocol, with no verbatim reproduction of any canonical
    passage. The same input produced recall from one model family and
    from-scratch design from another. A plausible-sounding problem description,
    written without reference to a famous solution, does not guarantee that the
    model will design from the problem alone; if the problem's shape is close
    enough to a canonical case the model has deeply seen in training, the
    canonical solution can surface without being asked for. When different
    model families behave differently on the same input, the difference is
    itself informative.
  </p>

  <p class="citation">
    <em>
      Seen in
      <a href={src('provenance/018-reference-validation-exercise-1/cell1/03-c3-test-result.md')}>Session 018's C3 test result</a>,
      comparing the
      <a href={src('provenance/018-reference-validation-exercise-1/cell1/c3-claude.md')}>Claude-family response</a>
      with the
      <a href={src('provenance/018-reference-validation-exercise-1/cell1/c3-codex.md')}>non-Claude response</a>
      given the same constraint statement.
    </em>
  </p>
</Base>
